  <detection>
    - Monitor for Frida/Objection process attachment
    - Check for root/jailbreak indicators
    - Implement integrity checks on app binary
    - Use certificate transparency logs
    - Monitor for debugger attachment
  </detection>

  <validation>
    - Successfully intercept HTTPS traffic in Burp
    - Capture API requests and responses
    - Modify requests without app errors
    - Document bypass method used
    - Test on multiple app versions
  </validation>

  <pro_tips>
    - Start with objection/Frida universal scripts
    - Flutter apps need special handling (reFlutter tool)
    - Some apps use multiple pinning layers - bypass all
    - Check for root/jailbreak detection before pinning bypass
    - Network Security Config bypass often simplest on Android
    - Use Android 7-9 for easier testing (before stricter pinning)
    - iOS apps may use App Transport Security + pinning
  </pro_tips>

  <remember>Modern mobile apps implement multiple security layers. Successful interception requires: 1) Root/jailbreak or advanced runtime manipulation, 2) Bypassing certificate pinning, 3) Potentially bypassing additional tamper detection. Always try the simplest method first (objection/Frida scripts) before attempting manual patches.</remember>
</vulnerability_guide>
